        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>The <strong>Keychron K8</strong> is half the price and adds wireless, but the trade-off is night and day in typing feel. The K8 is a great entry-level mechanical keyboard; the Q1 is a custom keyboard. If budget or wireless is the priority, the K8 wins. If typing feel is the priority, the Q1 wins. See our <a href="/reviews/keychron-k8-review/">Keychron K8 review</a> for the full breakdown.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Keychron Q1 Pro</strong> is the wireless version of the Q1 — same gasket mount, same aluminum body, plus Bluetooth 5.1 and a tilting screen for $50 more. If you need wireless, the Q1 Pro is the obvious choice. We tested the wired Q1 because it is the purer typing experience (no battery weight to rattle, no wireless firmware to maintain), but both are excellent.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Mode Envoy</strong> is a true custom kit at $310 (before switches and keycaps). It offers a more refined gasket mount, a wider range of plate materials, and a more premium finish. But you have to build it yourself, the wait is longer, and the typing feel is only marginally better than the Q1 for twice the price. The Q1 captures 90% of the custom experience for 50% of the cost.</p>

      <p>Pair the Q1 with the <a href="/reviews/best-wireless-mouse-work/">best wireless mouse for work</a> — we recommend the Logitech MX Master 3S, which shares the Q1's premium build quality and pairs well with a desk that values feel over everything else.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the Q1 if you spend 6+ hours a day typing and you care about how the keyboard feels and sounds. The gasket mount and aluminum body deliver an experience that no plastic board can match, and the hot-swap PCB means it is a foundation you can refine for years.</p>

      <p>Get the knob version. The $10 premium for the rotary encoder is the best value upgrade on the Q1. A volume knob you can use without looking is a small thing that adds up over a year of daily use.</p>

      <p>Start with Gateron GPro Brown switches if you are unsure. They are tactile (a bump at actuation), quiet enough for an office (52 dB), and a safe default that most typists like. Once you have lived with the Q1 for a month, use the hot-swap to experiment — linear reds for speed, silent reds for the quietest possible office, or tactile clears for a heavier bump. That experimentation is the whole point of a custom keyboard.</p>

      <p>Budget for keycaps. The stock ABS caps are the Q1's one real weakness, and a $40 PBT set transforms the board. Treat the Q1 as a $189 to $209 purchase (board plus keycaps) and the value still beats anything else at the price.</p>

      <p>Skip the Q1 if wireless is non-negotiable. The Q1 is wired USB-C only, and while the Q1 Pro adds Bluetooth, it costs $50 more and adds battery weight that subtly changes the sound. For a clean-desk multi-device workflow, the <a href="/reviews/logitech-mx-keys-s-review/">Logitech MX Keys S</a> or the <a href="/reviews/keychron-k8-review/">Keychron K8</a> are the better picks.</p>

      <p>Buy a <a href="/reviews/best-desk-pad-large/">large desk pad</a> at the same time. The Q1's weight means it will not slide on a bare desk, but a pad dampens residual resonance and protects the desk finish under a 1.6 kg aluminum board.</p>

